{
  "doc_id": "27012",
  "text": "APRIL (a proliferation-inducing ligand), also known as TNFSF13, TALL-2 and CD256, a member of tumor necrosis factor (TNF) superfamily, was first discovered and successfully cloned by Hahne et al in 1998 [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . It can induce cell proliferation and overexpressed in most tumor tissues or cells, especially in the digestive system carcinomas, such as colon carcinoma, pancreatic cancer, gastric cancer, hepatoma and esophageal carcinoma [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . APRIL plays an essential role in the occurrence and development of some tumors, including colon carcinoma. Given its great participation in these tumors, some researchers have reported that APRIL gene can be exploited as a therapeutic target [CITATION_9] .",
